    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3808149088" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3808149088" />
    <a title="Jess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41763158-jess"><img alt="Jess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611747988p2/41763158.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3808149088?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jess" href="/user/show/41763158-jess">Jess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=ww2">ww2</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=2021">2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3808149088" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10101114641404408350">I have very mixed feelings about this one. I greatly appreciate that this is not a romanticized pounce to capitalize on one of the greatest traumas of history. Working as a bookseller, I’ve seen any number of trends come and go, but the one that endures is the Holocaust. And sadly, only a minority are as honest as <i>Maus</i>. <br/><br/>Graphic novel form is a fascinating medium to use. I think we are all in agreement that language does not stretch far enough to describe - in any manner of adequacy – the horror </span>
  <span id="freeText10101114641404408350" style="display:none">I have very mixed feelings about this one. I greatly appreciate that this is not a romanticized pounce to capitalize on one of the greatest traumas of history. Working as a bookseller, I’ve seen any number of trends come and go, but the one that endures is the Holocaust. And sadly, only a minority are as honest as <i>Maus</i>. <br /><br />Graphic novel form is a fascinating medium to use. I think we are all in agreement that language does not stretch far enough to describe - in any manner of adequacy – the horror of these events. It’s difficult to envision, let alone articulate. I suppose I could rattle off a postmodernist spiel about Spiegelman’s medium, but I’ll save it – I don’t want to be <i>that</i> person. It is undeniably original and audacious to scale down such an expanse – but I am unsure to what extent it has communicated anything effective.<br /><br />a)	Spiegelman acknowledges how his father falls into the Jewish stereotype, in a way that is exceptionally honest. I was confused, then, why he chose to present Jews as mice – is it to present them as diminutive prey, or does it play into the discourse of vermin? <br /><br />b)	His relationship with his father is unambiguously difficult; it is a wonderful exploration of post-memory. Vladek’s character is not warped for the sake of likeability. And yet I found this a frustrating read on that basis. I did not care for any of the characters (?) – of course, that does not forgive anything that happened to them, but it did not invest me. <br /><br />There was one moment that I found particularly chilling, outside of the standard Holocaust narrative: Artie calls his father a ‘murderer’ on the basis that he destroyed his mother’s diaries, denying her a right to her own story. I’ll leave that one with you.<br /><br />I wish I had enjoyed this more. It makes me feel ignorant and selfish to admit that I did not, but I won’t apologise. There are other accounts/interpretations of the Holocaust that I found more disturbing, confronting, and compelling.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10101114641404408350" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

